<font color="#FF0000">REACTION TO PROTEST</font><br>
<tt>Sun Dec 22 19:19:48 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I can't help but comment on the writer who remembers the graphic depiction of a monk self emolating.  Yes,  the monks didn't get the religious freedom they wanted from the government we were supporting.  They were not allow to proseletyse,  like other religious groups then and now,  they had a polictical position as well.  The government of South Vietnam allowed them a limited voice in the issues of the times.  I can understand why the writer felt we shouldn't support such a government. Contrast this to the government of the North.  NO RELIGION was allowed.  This was the government we were fighting.  Sometimes,  not when you're thirteen,  you pick the lesser of two evils.  The US suppported Stalin during WWII,  not a nice guy,  but he was prepared to weigh in against Hitler and that was more important than whether he allowed the same freedoms we did.  The US,  as Robt. McNamara says in his apologetic book,  did in fact have a noble purpose.  That armed intervention was never going to produce the desired results eluded many at the time.  After the war,  Amnesty International declared the &quot;new&quot; Vietnamese government the &quot;most repressive on earth.&quot;  Viet Cong fighters fled the country,  many notable becasue of their high rank in the Viet Cong force.  They too believed the North would live up to what turned out to be their propaganda. Amnesty International can hardly be called a supporter of the US.  That was the government we fought against and for many, that was why we fought.  It is right and responsible to protest when you believe you must.  It is also responsible to know as many of the facts as possible before so doing.  The effect of the protests was to profer support for the North Vietnamese cause.  How many would today support what Amnesty International would declare the most repressive government on earth?  So while many continue to justify their willingness to provide support to the North Vietnamese and decry the US role as immoral,  I know that in the end,  the North Vietnamese turned out to be a government not supportable by men of good will anywhere.
<p><code>-- tsalamone@hypercom.com  (Tom Salamone) </code><p>


